{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491689","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491689"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:23:45+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:23:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1022"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1022","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1022"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.11,0.03,0.12,0.7]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1022"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109328"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1022","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1022"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1022"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91692"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"611"},{"type":"tags","id":"1253"},{"type":"tags","id":"4267"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"9143"},{"type":"tags","id":"9222"},{"type":"tags","id":"9315"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5211"},{"type":"contributions","id":"5530"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12319"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18125"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42200"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44492"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109328","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109328"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 18-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a five-day history of increasing pain when sitting and the feeling of a lump between his buttocks. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. On examination, he appears well with a pulse rate of 74/min, blood pressure 120/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.9\u00b0C. There is a palpable, tender, erythematous swelling 3 cm in diameter in the natal cleft which has started to discharge purulent material from its apex. There is no surrounding cellulitis.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Intravenous antibiotics","Endoscopic pilonidal sinus treatment","Aspiration for microscopy and culture","Excision and closure","Incision and drainage"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has an infected pilonidal sinus with abscess formation. The priority is to perform \u003Cstrong\u003Eincision and drainage\u003C/strong\u003E to evacuate the pus. Once the acute infection has settled, definitive treatment for removal of the sinus tract can be considered.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous antibiotics\u003C/strong\u003E are not indicated as there are no signs of systemic sepsis or surrounding cellulitis. Oral antibiotics (such as flucloxacillin) can be a useful adjunct when there is surrounding cellulitis, but \u003Cstrong\u003Eincision and drainage\u003C/strong\u003E is still the mainstay of treatment for an abscess.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEndoscopic pilonidal sinus treatment\u003C/strong\u003E is a minimally invasive technique used for definitive surgical management of chronic or recurrent pilonidal disease, but is not appropriate for acute pilonidal abscess.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAspiration\u003C/strong\u003E for microscopy and culture is not required as pilonidal abscess is a clinical diagnosis and empiric antibiotics (if indicated) can be selected to cover the typical causative organisms (skin flora).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDefinitive surgical management with \u003Cstrong\u003Eexcision of disease and closure\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate in the acute setting with an overlying abscess. The abscess should first be drained, with excision and closure performed electively at a later date if the patient has recurrent disease.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Clinical presentation of pilonidal sinus can vary from asymptomatic to acute abscess to recurrent disease.","Incision and drainage is the priority for an acute pilonidal abscess; antibiotics alone are insufficient."],"references":["Khanna A, Rombeau JL. Pilonidal disease. Clin Colon Rectal Surg. 2011 Mar;24(1):46-53. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/22379405/","Choi K, Srinath H. Pilonidal disease practice points: an update. AJGP. 2019 Mar;48(3). Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31256473/","Doll D, Friederichs J, Boulesteix A-L, D\u00fcsel W, Fend F, Petersen S. Surgery for asymptomatic pilonidal sinus disease. International journal of colorectal disease. 2008;23(9):839-844. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/18491116/","Parente G, Ruspi F, Thomas E, Di Mitri M, Cravano SM, D\u0027Antonio S, et al. Endoscopic Pilonidal Sinus Treatment: Preliminary Results, Learning Curve and Comparison with Standard Open Approach. Children (Basel). 2023 Jun 15;10(6):1063. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/37371294/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91692"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1022"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91692","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/91692"},"attributes":{"createdA